## Table conventions

### Structure

- Every table has a header row and a separator row
- Separator row uses dashes (`---`) padded to match the column width with spaces
- Every column is pipe-aligned with at least one space of padding on each side
- No empty cells ŌĆö use `ŌĆö` (em dash) for intentionally absent values

### Column naming

| Column name  | When to use                                          |
| ------------ | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| `Description`| Final column in most tables ŌĆö always the widest      |
| `Required`   | `Yes` or `No` ŌĆö never blank                          |
| `Nullable`   | `Yes` or `No` ŌĆö used in response body tables         |
| `Type`       | Data type of the field                               |
| `Format`     | Composite key format or value pattern                |
| `Rationale`  | Used only in domain model rules tables               |

### Placeholder rows

Template tables use plain descriptive text as placeholder values:

```markdown
| `field_name` | String | Yes/No | What this field represents |
```

Never use `...` or leave cells empty in template tables.

---

## Placeholder syntax

Placeholders always use `{PascalCase}` with curly braces. This applies to headings, prose, and table cells uniformly.

**Heading placeholders** identify the subject of the pattern or example:

| Pattern                        | Example result                    |
| ------------------------------ | --------------------------------- |
| `{TypePrefix}: {SubjectName}`  | `### Model: {EntityName}`         |
| `{SubjectName}` (free form)    | `### Consumer: {ConsumerName}`    |

**File-path placeholders** appear in naming conventions and documentation location sections:

| Placeholder | Meaning                                          |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| `{N}.{N}`   | Version prefix (e.g., `1.0`, `2.1`)             |
| `{name}`    | Kebab-case name of the subject being documented  |

**Table cell placeholders** follow the same `{PascalCase}` rule and describe expected content:

```markdown
| `{field_name}` | String | Yes/No | What this field represents        |
| `{part1}#{part2}` | ŌĆö   | ŌĆö      | Composite key segment description |
```

When defining a new spec type, introduce only the placeholders needed. Do not reuse placeholder names from other spec types for semantically different concepts.

